$$title: More Electrostatic Potential
$$use-outline: true

If a charge moves through a field and returns to its starting point
	W = 0
	<m>\oint</m> means line is closed
	<m>\oint \vec{E} \cdot \vec{dl} = 0</m>
	
	<m>\frac{dV}{dr} \vec{r} = -E</m>
	
	Equipotential lines always perpendicular to field lines because if you move only perpendicular to field lines, you do no work
	
	Somewhere in space at point P, potential V_P
		step in x direction
			<m>|E_x| = \frac{\Delta V}{\Delta x} | _{yz}</m>
				
	Units for E: N/C = V/m
	
	<m>\vec{E} = - \left( \frac{\partial V}{\partial x} \hat{x} + \frac{\partial V}{\partial y} \hat{y} + \frac{\partial V}{\partial z} \hat{z} \right)</m>
		<m>\vec{E} = -grad V</m>
	
	
	
